Problem Statement

For this particular assignment, the data of different types of wine sales in the 20th century is to be analysed. Both of these data are from the same company but of different wines. As an analyst in the ABC Estate Wines, you are tasked to analyse and forecast Wine Sales in the 20th century.

# Checking for Additive Decomposition Assumptions
print(f'Residual Mean = {residual.mean()}')
from scipy.stats import shapiro
sns.distplot(residual)
shapiro(residual.dropna())

Residual Mean = -1.2088458994707585
Out[721]:
ShapiroResult(statistic=0.9833056372432118, pvalue=0.03433683203799767)
Observations:
  • Residuals are not uniformly distributed around zero, showing patterns that might indicate model inadequacies. Shapiro-Wilk test returned p-value of 0.34 rejecting the null-hypothesis.
  • The residual histogram and density plot reveal that the residuals deviate from normality, further suggesting the additive model may not fully capture the underlying data characteristics.
  • Since Additive Decomposition assumption are note met we will explore Multiplicative Decomposition.

EDA Observations:

Overall Trends:

  • Sales data shows a moderate upward trend with clear seasonality, peaking in December each year.
  • The 12-month rolling mean indicates growth until the late 1980s, followed by stability.

Monthly and Yearly Trends:

  • Monthly sales spike in October and peak in December, with a mid-year dip from June to August.
  • Yearly trends show an incremental increase until the late 1980s, after which sales stabilize.

Statistical Insights:

  • The average monthly sales are around 2,000 units, with December consistently showing the highest sales.
  • Median yearly sales are around 2000 units, with upper outliers indicating occasional high sales periods.

Decomposition Analysis:

  • Additive decomposition assumptions were not met: residuals are not normally distributed (p-value = 0.34).
  • Multiplicative decomposition fits well: residuals are evenly distributed around 1 and approximately normal (p-value = 0.078).

Seasonal and Outlier Analysis:

  • Seasonal patterns show highest sales in October, November, and December.
  • Outliers are present in January, February, and July, indicating occasional deviations from normal sales patterns.

Stationarity Check on Training Dataset

In[797]:
# Function to check staionarity
def test_stationarity(timeseries):

    #determining roll statistics
    rolmean = timeseries.rolling(window=12).mean()
    rolstd = timeseries.rolling(window=12).std()

    ##plot rolling Statistics:
    orig = plt.plot(timeseries,color='blue',label='Original')
    mean = plt.plot(rolmean, color='red', label='Rolling Mean')
    std = plt.plot(rolstd, color='black', label='Rolling Std')
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.title('Rolling Mean and Standard Deviation', fontsize=17)
    plt.show(block=False)

    #Perform Dickey-Fuller Test:
    print('Results of Dickey Fuller Test:')
    dftest = adfuller(timeseries, autolag='AIC')
    dfoutput = pd.Series(dftest[0:4], index=['Test Statistic','p-value','#Lags Used','Number of Observations Used'])
    for key,value in dftest[4].items():
        dfoutput['Critical Value (%s)'%key] = value
    print(dfoutput,'\n')
In[798]:
# Test stationarity on Sparkling training dataset
test_stationarity(train_dfs['Sparkling'])

Results of Dickey Fuller Test:
Test Statistic                 -1.2089
p-value                         0.6697
#Lags Used                     12.0000
Number of Observations Used   119.0000
Critical Value (1%)            -3.4865
Critical Value (5%)            -2.8862
Critical Value (10%)           -2.5799
dtype: float64

Hypothesis:

H0 = Series is not stationary

H1 = Series is stationary

Observations:

  • High p-value of 0.6697 fails to reject the null-hypothesis and confirms the Time Series is not Stationary.
  • We will apply differncing in the next step in attempt to make the Time Series Stationary.
In[800]:
# Apply Differencing on Training Dataset
train_dfs_diff = train_dfs.diff().dropna()
train_dfs_diff_test = adfuller(train_dfs_diff,regression='ct')
print(f'DF test statistics is: {train_dfs_diff_test[0]}')
print(f'DF test p-value is: {train_dfs_diff_test[1]}')
print(f'Number of lags used is: {train_dfs_diff_test[2]}')
if train_dfs_diff_test[1] <= 0.05:
    print('The Differenced Time Series is Stationary now.')
else:
    print('The Time Series is Not Stationary')

Business Insights and Recommendations

  • Actionable Insights
  • Business Recommendations

Actionable Insights:

Dataset Overview:

  • The dataset consists of monthly sales data for sparkling wine from January 1980 to July 1995.
  • Summary statistics show an average monthly sales of around 2,000 units with noticeable seasonal peaks.

Data Quality:

  • There were no duplicate or missing values, which facilitated smooth model development and analysis.

Seasonal and Trend Patterns:

  • Yearly and monthly analyses reveal consistent seasonal patterns, with sales peaking in December and lower sales observed in mid-year months.
  • Although there was no clear year on year trend, sales seems to have gradually risen between 1982 till 1987 than started falling across most months.
  • These patterns were effectively captured by the Triple Exponential Smoothing model, underscoring its suitability for this dataset.

Model Performance:

  • The final model selected was the Tuned Triple Exponential Smoothing (TES) model with parameters Alpha=0.3, Beta=0.3, and Gamma=0.3. This model achieved the lowest RMSE of 361.3973, indicating superior accuracy.
  • Automated TES and Automated SARIMA models also showed reasonably good performance with RMSE of 404.2868 and 611.1517 respectively. With further tuning these models can be improved.

Business Recommendations:

Adopt the Tuned TES Model:

  • Implement the Tuned Triple Exponential Smoothing (TES) model with parameters Alpha=0.3, Beta=0.3, and Gamma=0.3 for future sales forecasting due to its superior accuracy.

Inventory Managemnt:

  • Forecast Sales derived from the Tuned TES model suggest boost of sales during last quarter. Use forecast to optimize inventory levels, ensuring adequate stock during peak demand periods while minimizing overstock during low-demand months.
  • Align resource allocation, including staffing and logistics, with forecasted sales patterns to improve operational efficiency.

Promotional Strategies:

  • Plan marketing and promotional activities around forecasted sales peaks to maximize their impact.Use insights from the model to schedule promotions during anticipated low-demand periods to boost sales.

Further Model Enhancement:

  • Regularly update the model with new sales data to maintain and improve forecast accuracy.
  • Explore incorporating additional variables, such as economic indicators or promotional event data, to enhance the models predictive capabilities.

Continuous Monitoring:

  • Monitor the performance of the TES model regularly and adjust the parameters as needed based on changes in sales patterns or external factors.
  • Perform periodic reviews of the forecast accuracy and make necessary adjustments to ensure continued reliability.

Market Expansion Analysis:

  • Use the forecasting model to simulate potential sales in new markets or demographics, aiding in strategic market expansion decisions.
  • Analyze customer purchasing behavior insights provided by the model to tailor engagement strategies and increase customer loyalty.

Investigate Outliers:

  • Analyze periods with significant residual spikes to identify underlying causes, such as unexpected events or promotions, and adjust future forecasts accordingly.
  • Use this analysis to improve model accuracy and incorporate such factors into future forecasts.
